args: Thank you one and all for coming to this\ncelebration of the newfound friendship\nbetween Alberia and Fadden!
Let us raise our glasses in a toast to our\ncontinued prosperity and friendship!
My, but you Fadden nobles certainly\nare skilled dancers!
I can't remember the last time I enjoyed\nmyself so much on the floor.
I am honored to be complimented by one\nas discerning as you, Princess Chelle.
And despite your humble modesty, Leif,\nI was quite impressed by you as well.
Though it wouldn't have hurt for you\nto dress up a bit more.
Forgive me, Princess, but this is the proper\ndress uniform for a knight such as myself.
You're quite the gentleman, aren't you?\nHow simply divine!
Princess Chelle, thank you again for\narranging such a lavish party in our honor.
Chanzelia truly is the radiant city!\nEverything here shines so brightly...\nI'm actually a touch envious.
Ah, but I've heard the palace in Fadden\nis quite the sight to behold as well—in\nparticular your stained glass works.
I understand this selfsame glass can be\nfound at the August Cathedral in the\nHoly City of Grams. Is that correct?
Indeed it is—and I pray our newfound\nalliance will soon permit Fadden glass\nto bedeck the halls in Chanzelia as well.
Far better here than in that wretched city...
Strong words indeed. Do you truly find\nGrams to be so intolerable?
Ah, but I seem to remember your country\nis reliant on them—a relationship you\nseek to free yourselves from.
You understand the situation correctly,\nPrincess—and I imagine that is, in part,\nwhy you have deigned to invite is here?
I imagined you would appreciate it.\nChanzelia, too, has deep ties to Grams,\nafter all.
Perhaps you would be so good as to\ninform me what YOU hoped to achieve\nby accepting my invitation.
I think you already know: Fadden is a harsh\nand barren land, and we depend on Grams\nfor most of our food imports.
Because of that, they have felt the need\nto become increasingly involved in our\ndomestic affairs.

Our attempts to create trade routes with
other countries have been bogged down
by wars and having to curry favor
with Grams.
Yes, it's never easy to cut ties.
Indeed. Our country boasts skilled\ncraftsmen, as well as rich mineral\ndeposits for creating artistic marvels.
Yet what good is such beauty if a person\nis not truly free to enjoy it? One cannot\nmake a meal of stained glass, after all.

I will speak plain: We seek a way free of
our current situation, a way to ensure our
people go hungry no longer. And we feel
this alliance would serve just that end.
You are a kind and caring princess.\nAnd you may rest assured.
Once our alliance becomes official, I will\nimmediately establish new supply routes\nbetween Chanzelia and Fadden.
This is almost too good to be true.\nOh, but I am so relieved!
Was something in particular troubling you?
Even in North Grastaea, we hear tell of\nChanzelia and its wondrous manacasters.

Tongues wag with tales of the princess
who has excavated these weapons and
seeks to develop new ones, so I'd thought
to find you a bit...well...rougher.
But having met you in person, I now\nrealize that reputation is unearned.
You dance beautifully and rule prudently.\nTHAT is the true nature of the manacaster-\ntoting princess I've heard so much about.
My, that's quite the epithet.\nBut does that not describe you as well?
I hear that Fadden is hard at work\nexcavating its own manacasters.
Excavating, yes—but nothing more.\nOur technology isn't yet at the level\nwhere we can make use of them.
In truth, I pray for a world in which\nwe NEVER have to use them.
And I as well. My interest in manacasters\nis driven by curiosity more than anything.
It's natural for people to seek knowledge, \njust as it's natural for them to seek peace.
Princess Chelle, I think this may be the\nbeginning of a wonderful friendship.
And as we are becoming closer,\nmight I ask you one thing?
Are you and Leif perchance betrothed?
Not at all. I am a princess and he\nis my knight—nothing more.
Oh... I was entirely convinced you were in\na relationship out of a romance novel.
It is rather rare for a knight to escort\nhis charge to a function such as this.
Leif is the most trustworthy man I know,\nwhich is why I wanted him at my side.
One never knows what might happen at a\ndiplomatic party.
You surprise me, Princess Yelda!\nI'd not pegged you as one who engaged\nin idle court gossip.
Everyone enjoys a good love story,\ndo they not?
Alas, love often doesn't work out for\nprincesses like us. Mine certainly didn't.
So if you two actually WERE a couple,\nI would cheer you both on until my throat\nwas hoarse!
Well, I can see I read too much into the\nsituation. Perhaps I'll go have another\ndance to cool my head.
Let us take the floor as well, Leif.
I trust you remember the dance\nI taught you?
...Do you truly mean to form an alliance\nwith Fadden, Princess?
If something about the situation is\ntroubling you, Leif, be out with it.
Do not mistake me—Princess Yelda\ncertainly seems to be a woman of honor.
And yet, I cannot help but think\nthere is another side to her.
And what is the reason for this suspicion?
Fadden fiercely resents the meddling of\nthe Holy City of Grams, as you well know.
So it's perfectly understandable why they\nwould seek to form new alliances.
But that being said, why Alberia?\nOur current situation is... Well...

You're saying there's no merit to seeking 
an alliance with a country that so 
recently was ruled by a demon god and
whose throne currently sits empty?

A touch blunter than I was looking for,
but yes. Additionally, I've not heard
anything about Fadden engaging in actual
revolt against their Grams overseers.
They have animosity, yet it hasn't moved\nthem to action. There must be a reason.
Which is part of why I asked them here.
Then you will form the alliance even with\nsuch questions still swirling about?
How else am I to get to the bottom\nof what is really going on?

The meetings to formalize the alliance
begin tomorrow—and believe me, Leif,
I will be watching what they say and do
with GREAT interest.
